I think a lot about millennials who were the last generation to be able to form connections with artists, without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during a golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We would directly immerse ourselves in things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't so easy to determine.
Without having a reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships became the foundations for our lives.
That's why we are so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on air, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the show every Thursday.
It was nothing like what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and where everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specified closed spaces.
unconsciously we are dying to connect to the universal community surrounding all of this
that's why so many of us watch shows like The Office or movies like Celebrity Presenter obsessively, full of short references, like memes.
we repeated these references, knowing that most people knew them
now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
there are too many things to see and no way to rationalize everything... will we escape hypersaturation?
we get caught in cycles of discovering new media, only to end up realizing that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
we are forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while acknowledging that the people who created the art we connect with can be very imperfect.
we enter parasocial relationships by paying more attention.
one understands that it's hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without crushing others along the way.
due to a lack of collective awareness in the media, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us stay critical.
some of us continue to put people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall off.
we are going through a turbulent period and I can't wait to find out where it will take us.
